<p style="font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; margin-top: 20px; margin-bottom: 12px;"><span style="color: #c90431; font-size: 22px;">We&rsquo;ve got <a style="color: #c90431;" href="https://corpapp.honeywell.com/sites/honvideo/Pages/Player.aspx?bctid=4847727054001&amp;UsrId=e045068&amp;ItmId=5919" target="_blank">60-seconds</a> to talk about how good communication starts with GOOD WRITING.</span> <br /></p>
<p style="font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; margin-top: 12px;">We&rsquo;ve been writing all our lives, so it seems simple. But most of the business letters that get written are really pretty bad.</p>
<p style="font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; margin-top: 4px;">Here&rsquo;s why: Far too often we write to impress people. We make it formal, we use BIG words, and we complicate thoughts to make us look smart.</p>
<p style="font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 14px; margin-top: 4px;">But the only thing we convince them of is that we&rsquo;re bad communicators.<br /><br /></p>
